{"title":"Pro bike check: Michael Matthews’ Giant Propel Advanced SL","link":"https://www.cyclingtips.com/2023/05/pro-bike-check-michael-matthews-giant-propel-advanced-sl/","date":1684375139000,"content":"<figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Michael-Matthews-Giant-propel-advanced-sl-bike-ZW-Photography-00516.jpg?width=1200\" alt=\"Pro bike check: Michael Matthews' Giant Propel Advanced SL\" /></figure><p><a href=\"http://cyclingtips.com/tag/Michael-Matthews\" target=\"_blank\">Michael Matthews</a> is always a threat in a grand tour.</p>\n<p>Need proof? Just look at his performance at stage 3 of the Giro d’Italia where he pipped Mads Pedersen for his third career individual Giro stage win.</p>\n<p>The 32-year-old Australian sprinter is racing this year’s Giro aboard the <a href=\"https://www.cyclingtips.com/2022/12/2023-giant-propel-advanced-sl-long-term-review/\" target=\"_blank\">Giant Propel Advanced SL</a>, the aero bike of choice for his Jayco-AlUla team.</p>\n<p>The bike is built with a Shimano Dura-Ace Di2 groupset, Cadex wheels and saddle, and Vittoria tires. Take a look below for a full gallery of Michael Matthews’ Giant Propel Advanced SL race bike for the Giro d’Italia.</p>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Michael-Matthews-Giant-propel-advanced-sl-bike-ZW-Photography-00516.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Michael Matthews Giant Propel Advanced SL Bike\" width=\"1800\" height=\"1200\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Michael-Matthews-Giant-propel-advanced-sl-bike-ZW-Photography-00516.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Michael-Matthews-Giant-propel-advanced-sl-bike-ZW-Photography-00516.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption>Michael Matthews’ Giant Propel Advanced SL is built with a Shimano Dura-Ace Di2 groupset, Cadex wheels and saddle, and Vittoria tires. (Photo: Zac Williams)</figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/ZW-Photography-00572-scaled.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Michael Matthews Giant Propel Advanced SL Bike\" width=\"2560\" height=\"1707\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/ZW-Photography-00572-scaled.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/ZW-Photography-00572-scaled.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>Matthews was running 28c Vittoria Corsa Pros set up tubeless. Things have certainly changed quickly around tire choice these past few seasons. </span>(Photo: Zac Williams)</figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Michael-Matthews-Giant-propel-advanced-sl-bike-ZW-Photography-00524.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Michael Matthews Giant Propel Advanced SL Bike\" width=\"1800\" height=\"1200\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Michael-Matthews-Giant-propel-advanced-sl-bike-ZW-Photography-00524.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Michael-Matthews-Giant-propel-advanced-sl-bike-ZW-Photography-00524.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption>Matthews opts for 54/40T chainrings on a Shimano Dura-Ace power meter crankset. (Photo: Zac Williams)</figcaption></figure>\n<p><strong>Also read: <a href=\"https://www.cyclingtips.com/2023/05/bike-check-rigobert-urans-cannondale-supersix-evo-lab71/\" target=\"_blank\">Bike check: Rigoberto Uran’s Cannondale Supersix Evo Lab71</a></strong></p>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Michael-Matthews-Giant-propel-advanced-sl-bike-ZW-Photography-00535.jpg?width=730\" alt width=\"1800\" height=\"1200\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Michael-Matthews-Giant-propel-advanced-sl-bike-ZW-Photography-00535.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Michael-Matthews-Giant-propel-advanced-sl-bike-ZW-Photography-00535.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption>Matthews is running a thoroughly modern drop bar with the addition of satellite sprint shifters. (Photo: Zac Williams)</figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/ZW-Photography-00568-scaled.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Michael Matthews Giant Propel Advanced SL Bike\" width=\"2560\" height=\"1707\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/ZW-Photography-00568-scaled.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/ZW-Photography-00568-scaled.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption>Those brake hoods are quite toed in, something you generally only see on pro set ups. Giant supplies the handlebar tape in addition to the frame. (Photo: Zac Williams)</figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/ZW-Photography-00541-scaled.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Michael Matthews Giant Propel Advanced SL Bike\" width=\"2560\" height=\"1707\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/ZW-Photography-00541-scaled.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/ZW-Photography-00541-scaled.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>Cadex says the Boost saddle is more efficient in transferring power, while still being comfortable. Have your cake and eat it too it seems. </span>(Photo: Zac Williams)</figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/ZW-Photography-00574-scaled.jpg?width=730\" alt width=\"2560\" height=\"1707\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/ZW-Photography-00574-scaled.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/ZW-Photography-00574-scaled.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption><span>The Cadex 50 Ultra wheels, like the name suggests, are 50mm deep and are a good choice for sprint stages. </span>(Photo: Zac Williams)</figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Michael-Matthews-Giant-propel-advanced-sl-bike-ZW-Photography-00552.jpg?width=730\" alt=\"Michael Matthews Giant Propel Advanced SL Bike\" width=\"1800\" height=\"1200\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Michael-Matthews-Giant-propel-advanced-sl-bike-ZW-Photography-00552.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Michael-Matthews-Giant-propel-advanced-sl-bike-ZW-Photography-00552.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption>One unusual touch for an aero bike in this day and age is the non-aerodynamic handlebar. The stem and handlebar are also two different components rather than integrated. The computer mount is nicely attached to the stem, however. (Photo: Zac Williams)</figcaption></figure>\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Michael-Matthews-Giant-propel-advanced-sl-bike-ZW-Photography-00537.jpg?width=730\" alt width=\"1800\" height=\"1200\" srcset=\"https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Michael-Matthews-Giant-propel-advanced-sl-bike-ZW-Photography-00537.jpg?width=650 650w, https://cdn.cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Michael-Matthews-Giant-propel-advanced-sl-bike-ZW-Photography-00537.jpg?width=190 190w\" /><figcaption>One more angle in all its aero glory. (Photo: Zac Williams)</figcaption></figure>\n<p><strong>Also read: <a href=\"https://www.cyclingtips.com/2023/05/bike-check-remco-evenepoels-world-champion-specialized-tarmac-sl7/\" target=\"_blank\">Bike check: Remco Evenepoel’s world champion Specialized Tarmac SL7</a></strong></p>","author":"Will Tracy","siteTitle":"CyclingTips","siteHash":"30feca30fb3902119bf2da6559e7337232527b61c9abe0a00f5d7543c6aa6c84","entryHash":"d70a34b4dc8b60d82c2807410be50719f9d4917f2ec606ac8c560b58220c8912","category":"Cycling"}